                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                    <title2
                                        cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                        jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-04-18T10:59:25.426-04:00"
                                        jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                        jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                        jcr:title="Supporting the most vulnerable"
                                        sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                        type="h2"
                                        variant="h"/>
                                    <text2
                                        cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                        jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:02:36.544-05:00"
                                        jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                        jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                        sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                        text="&lt;p>The COVID-19 pandemic has taken its toll on everyday life for people around the world. Many have sheltered in place by choice or order, staying in their homes for days and weeks, only leaving to work or get food or medicine.&lt;br>&#xa;&lt;br>&#xa;Now imagine that you don’t have a place to call home.&lt;br>&#xa;&lt;br>&#xa;This scenario is real for the growing number of people served by Chicago nonprofit Breakthrough, which runs two shelters for people experiencing homelessness and supports over 11,000 people through its food bank. When COVID-19 hit, Breakthrough staff feared an outbreak among guests in the shelters, Associate Director Bradley Troast says.&lt;br>&#xa;&lt;br>&#xa;“With close living quarters, many people with underlying conditions, mental and behavioral health issues, there’s limited access to health care if you were to get sick,” Troast says. “It’s a very vulnerable population.”&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                        textIsRich="true"/>
                                    <title2_316328686
                                        cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825694]"
                                        jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-04-18T10:59:36.407-04:00"
                                        jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                        jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                        jcr:title="Love Beyond Walls: Letting love flow"
                                        sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                        type="h2"
                                        variant="h"/>
                                </container>
                            </container4>
                            <image
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T21:55:55.598-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:05:40.405-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/image/v2/image"
                                alt="COVID-19 Community Resilience Fund"
                                altValueFromDAM="false"
                                displayPopupTitle="true"
                                fileReference="/content/dam/abbvie-com2/images/stories/the-hardest-hit-how-nonprofits-rise-to-the-challenge-of-covid-19/the_hardest_hit_stat_16x9.jpg"
                                isDecorative="false"
                                titleValueFromDAM="true"/>
                            <container
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:05:48.667-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:05:48.667-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <text
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:06:34.491-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:07:16.255-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Breakthrough is just one of 26 nonprofits benefitting from&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.abbvie.com/covid-19crf.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; title=&quot;AbbVie’s COVID-19 Community Resilience Fund. &quot;>AbbVie’s COVID-19 Community Resilience Fund&lt;/a>. The $5 million in total funding supports each nonprofit’s fight against the virus, focused on helping frontline health care workers and vulnerable populations in hard-hit communities.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Four of these organizations detail how AbbVie grants helped them bring life-saving services and support to people in critical need around the globe.&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container>
                            <image_423542518
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:07:34.339-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:08:24.084-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                jcr:title="Chicago nonprofit Breakthrough used AbbVie funding to purchase PPE, hygiene items and meals to support the vulnerable homeless and shelter population."
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/image/v2/image"
                                alt=" AbbVie’s COVID-19 Community Resilience Fund. "
                                altValueFromDAM="false"
                                displayPopupTitle="true"
                                fileReference="/content/dam/abbvie-com2/images/stories/the-hardest-hit-how-nonprofits-rise-to-the-challenge-of-covid-19/breakthrough_edit.jpg"
                                isDecorative="false"
                                titleValueFromDAM="false"/>
                            <container_769055376
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:08:31.547-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:08:31.547-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:08:57.912-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-04-18T10:59:47.218-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Breakthrough: A new normal to keep the doors open"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:09:29.265-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:09:38.758-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>An AbbVie grant enabled Breakthrough to purchase personal protective equipment (PPE) and hygiene items, including masks, soap and toothbrushes. With many sanitizing and distancing measures in place since March, fast forward to today and there have been no COVID-19 cases at either of Breakthrough’s shelters.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Now, staff focus on best serving people within the confines of Illinois’ COVID-19 restrictions, among some of the strictest in the United States that includes two separate stay-at-home orders. This means finding alternatives to critical programs like a community meal prepared by volunteers – instead, Breakthrough used funding from AbbVie and others to buy meals from local restaurants, providing nearly 9,900 meals from March through June and boosting local businesses.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Despite changes to community activities and meals and the necessity of social distancing, people who stay at Breakthrough still feel it’s a place where they can relax, Troast says.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>“It makes me appreciate the men and women who work in our shelters and how they’ve adapted,” he says. “This has been a great effort.”&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container_769055376>
                            <image_946465321
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:09:54.244-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:11:30.874-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                jcr:title="Boston Medical Center medical staff prepare to care for COVID-19 positive homeless people at a medical facility recently converted to a recovery center."
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/image/v2/image"
                                alt="Breakthrough: A new normal to keep the doors open"
                                altValueFromDAM="false"
                                displayPopupTitle="true"
                                fileReference="/content/dam/abbvie-com2/images/stories/the-hardest-hit-how-nonprofits-rise-to-the-challenge-of-covid-19/nonprofit_BMC.JPG"
                                isDecorative="false"
                                titleValueFromDAM="false"/>
                            <container_744509744
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:12:08.900-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:12:08.900-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:12:40.257-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-04-18T10:59:56.705-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Boston Medical Center: A place to rest and recover"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:12:45.391-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:15:34.042-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>In another major U.S. city, health care officials at Boston Medical Center (BMC) braced for a surge of COVID-19 cases last spring. BMC leaders knew the local homeless population would be disproportionately affected by the virus, with no place to recuperate and quarantine.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>An infusion of funding from AbbVie supported a creative solution: Temporarily reclaim BMC’s vacant East Newton Pavilion, which it sold to the state in 2018. Plans to transform the structure into a new psychiatric hospital were placed on hold, and instead BMC converted it into a recovery area carefully laid out for infection control, staffed with medical specialists and equipment, beds, furniture, food and drinks.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Time was of the essence to get the unit up and running, says Miriam Komaromy, MD, FACP, DFASAM, Medical Director at Boston Medical Center’s Grayken Center for Addiction and clinical lead for the pavilion. Just two weeks after gaining access to the pavilion, BMC opened the doors.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>About 225 COVID-19 positive people without homes took respite there during an 8-week period. Not only were they able to recover from the virus, many were able to get treatment for existing substance abuse disorders and mental illness, with 80% of patients presenting clear evidence of mental illness, Komaromy says.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>People stayed at the unit an average of 1 week; while all came in without a home, about one-quarter left with a stable place to stay, Komaromy says, made possible by the hard work of volunteer case managers who found long-term treatment options or family and friends to take their loved one in.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>BMC medical and support staff donated time on top of their regular responsibilities to take on shifts at the pavilion, motivated by a grateful group of patients, Komaromy says.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>“We heard from them again and again how grateful they were to have a place to stay, that they wouldn’t be infecting other people,” she says. “This generosity of heart was really touching to hear.”&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container_744509744>
                            <image_623731273
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:16:04.176-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
