                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                jcr:title="UNICEF ambassador to Benin, West Africa, Zeynab Abib and 8-year-old singer Fifa La Lune record a song about COVID-19 prevention measures."
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/image/v2/image"
                                alt="Boston Medical Center: A place to rest and recover"
                                altValueFromDAM="false"
                                displayPopupTitle="true"
                                fileReference="/content/dam/abbvie-com2/images/stories/the-hardest-hit-how-nonprofits-rise-to-the-challenge-of-covid-19/UNICEF_body.jpg"
                                isDecorative="false"
                                titleValueFromDAM="false"/>
                            <container_821512474
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:17:02.057-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:17:02.057-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:17:26.196-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-04-18T11:00:09.480-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="UNICEF: Young voices speak up"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:17:51.854-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:18:11.581-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Knowledge can mean the difference between life and death. This message is especially critical for global humanitarian organization UNICEF, with a mission of saving children’s lives around the world through education and access to basic nutrition, clean water, vaccines and more.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Early and flexible funding from AbbVie helped UNICEF respond to the coronavirus pandemic globally including in countries such as Brazil, Greece, Syria and Kenya, through infection prevention training and PPE.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Notably, support from companies like AbbVie was also key for UNICEF’s launch of a massive educational health effort for children and teens worldwide. The innovative program teaches everything from mask-wearing to hand hygiene to social distancing. Youth then take this information back to their families.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>“Having that immediate trust and partnership, and ability to start work as soon as possible, was extremely important to us,” says UNICEF Director of Corporate Partnerships Justine Feighery. “COVID-19 is hitting the most vulnerable population in every country. Having funding from AbbVie allows us to respond to that.”&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>UNICEF has tailored special programs to different parts of the world, like in Benin, West Africa, where the organization sponsored a YouTube music video performed by an 8-year-old singer, Fifa La Lune, and the organization’s national ambassador a singer/songwriter Zeynab Abib. The children’s song describes COVID-19 prevention measures that everyday people can take. UNICEF also sponsored a video contest challenging young people to come up with their own COVID-19 messaging.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>“The energy around children and teenagers is powerful,” Feighery says. “Their voices are really strong; their beliefs are really powerful. They become very engaged in activities like this.”&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container_821512474>
